  </figure>
</div>`}
/>

## Techniques in play

- **`grid-cols-[repeat(auto-fit,minmax(10rem,1fr))]`** — the gallery picks its own column count.
- **`col-span-2`** promotes the first tile to a featured size.
- **`object-cover` + `aspect-*`** crop every image to a uniform shape, no matter its native ratio —
  this is what makes galleries look orderly.
- **`group` + `group-hover:`** (a Module 4 preview) reveals the caption when the *figure* is hovered,
  not just the caption itself.
- **`absolute inset-x-0 bottom-0`** pins captions to the bottom edge.

<Callout type="insight" title="`object-cover` is how pros tame user-uploaded images">

In real products, images come in every conceivable size and ratio. The amateur lets them squish or
overflow; the professional fixes a container aspect ratio and uses `object-cover` so every image
crops to fill predictably. Combine that with a `auto-fit` grid and you have a gallery that looks
intentional with *zero* per-image babysitting — exactly the kind of robust default you want when
content is out of your control.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="Why pair `aspect-square` with `object-cover` on gallery images?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'To make images load faster', correct: false },
		{ text: 'To force a uniform shape and crop any image to fill it without distortion', correct: true },
		{ text: 'To convert images to squares on the server', correct: false },
		{ text: 'It is required for grid to work', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="The aspect utility fixes the box shape; object-cover crops the image to fill it cleanly."
/>

## Recap & module wrap-up

Module 3 done. You can place anything: flexbox for one axis, grid for two, positioning for overlays
and sticky elements, and `object-cover` for orderly media.

Next module: **Responsive & State** — make all of this adapt to every screen and react to the user.
